Including plots

You can also embed plots, for example:

# This is my first ggplot!
ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_point( aes(x=displ, y=hwy, color = class) )

Compare these two plots:

# Plot 1
ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_point( aes(x=displ, y=hwy), size = 5 ) 

# Plot 2
ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_point( aes(x=displ, y=hwy, size = displ ) )

YOUR TURN

Using the mpg data frame with x=displ, y=hwy, generate the following ggplots (each item is a separate plot). You can always see the first few rows of the data frame by typing glimpse(mpg) at the console (as we did above), or ?mpg for the documentation on the particular data frame. I’ve included the started code from earlier that you need to then modify.

  1. A plot that uses color to distinguish the class of the car.
ggplot(data = mpg ) + 
  geom_point( aes(x=displ, y=hwy, color = class))

  1. A plot that makes all the points red.
ggplot(data = mpg ) + 
  geom_point( aes(x=displ, y=hwy), color = "red")

  1. A plot that makes all the shapes to be filled triangles. (What would it be if the shape was just a triangle with a border?)
ggplot(data = mpg,aes(x=displ, y=hwy)) +
  geom_point(shape = 17)

  1. A plot that makes all the points to be 3 mm in size (that is you will need size=3).
ggplot(data = mpg ) + 
  geom_point( aes(x=displ, y=hwy, size = 3))

  1. A plot that makes all the points red, makes all the shapes filled triangles, and the size to be three.
ggplot(data = mpg ) + 
  geom_point( aes(x=displ, y=hwy), color = "red", shape = 17, size = 3)

  1. A plot that uses color to distinguish the class of the car, and makes all of the points filled squares.
ggplot(data = mpg ) + 
  geom_point( aes(x=displ, y=hwy, color = class), shape = 15)

  1. A plot that uses shapes to distinguish the class of the car, and color to distinguish the fuel type.
ggplot(data = mpg ) + 
  geom_point(aes(x=displ, y=hwy, shape = class, color = hwy))
## Warning: The shape palette can deal with a maximum of 6 discrete values because
## more than 6 becomes difficult to discriminate; you have 7. Consider
## specifying shapes manually if you must have them.

  1. One other aesthetic for geom_point is alpha, which is transparency on a scale from 0 to 1. Can you make a ggplot that from the mpg data frame that incorporates the aesthetics of alpha, color, shape, size?
ggplot(data = mpg ) + 
  geom_point( aes(x=displ, y=hwy, alpha = class), color = "blue", shape = 17, size = 2)
